Definition 2.2. For $(M,\mathcal{A})$ as above, we define (a) a relation $E\subset(I\times I)$ by: $(i,j)\in E$ iff $U_{i}=U_{j}$ (i.e., both charts have same domain, but need not coincide as charts), (b) a relation $L\subset(I\times I)$ by: $(i^{\prime},i)\in L$ iff [$U_{i^{\prime}}\subset U_{i}$, and $\forall y\in U_{i^{\prime}}:\phi_{i^{\prime}}(y)=\phi_{i}(y)$] (i.e., one chart is included in the other; this implies $V_{i^{\prime}}\subset V_{i}$).
Definition A.1. An ordered groupoid is a groupoid $(G_{0},G_{1},\pi_{0},\pi_{1},\delta,\ast)$ together with partial order relations $L$ (or $\leq$) on the sets $G_{0}$ and on $G_{1}$, such that: (OG0) $\forall x,y\in G_{0}$: $x\leq y$ iff $\delta(x)\leq\delta(y)$, (OG1) $g\leq h$ iff $g^{-1}\leq h^{-1}$, (OG2) if $g\leq h$, $g^{\prime}\leq h^{\prime}$ and if $g\ast g^{\prime}$ and $h\ast h^{\prime}$ are defined, then $g\ast g^{\prime}\leq h\ast h^{\prime}$, (OG3) for all morphisms $g:x\to y$ and all objects $x^{\prime}$ with $x^{\prime}\leq x$, there exists a unique morphism $g^{\prime}:x^{\prime}\to y^{\prime}$ with $g^{\prime}\leq g,y^{\prime}\leq y$: $\xymatrix{x\ar@{-}[d]^{L}\ar[r]^{g}&y\ar@{.}[d]^{L}\\ x^{\prime}\ar@{.>}[r]^{g^{\prime}}&y^{\prime}}$
Definition 4.2. A $(V,G)$-manifold is a set $M$ with a maximal $G$-atlas. A smooth manifold (over $\mathbb{K}$) is a $(V,G)$-manifold, where $V$ is a topological $\mathbb{K}$-module over a topological ring $\mathbb{K}$, and $G$ the pseudogroup of locally defined diffeomorphisms of $V$.
Definition 1.1. An equivalence-partially ordered set (e-pos) is a set $I$ together with an equivalence relation $E$ and a partial order $L$ (or $\leq$) on $I$ satisfying (Epos) $\quad$ if $i^{\prime}\leq i$ and $(i,j)\in E$, then there exists a unique $j^{\prime}\in I$ such that: $\,(i^{\prime},j^{\prime})\in E$ and $j^{\prime}\leq j$.
Definition 5.5. We say that $f$ is atlas-continuous if, for all $x\in M$ and all $j\in I^{\prime}$ with $f(x)\in V_{j}$, there exists $i\in I$ with $x\in V_{i}$ and $f(V_{i})\subset V_{j}$ (that is, $(j,i)\in F$).
Definition 6.5. Wih notation as in Definition 6.1 and Theorem 6.2, assume that $M=M^{\prime}$, $V=V^{\prime}$, $\mathcal{A}=\mathcal{A}^{\prime}$. Then the collection $(f_{k^{\prime}k})$ with $(k^{\prime},k)\in F$ such that $k\leq k^{\prime}$ are called restricted morphism data, or similarity data.
Definition 2.1. A chart of a set $M$, modelled on $V$ is a bijection $\phi:U\to W$ of a subset $U\subset M$ onto a subset $W\subset V$. An atlas on $M$ is a collection of charts $\mathcal{A}=(\phi_{i}:U_{i}\to V_{i})_{i\in I}$, or $(U_{i},\phi_{i},V_{i})_{i\in I}$, such that: (1) $[\phi_{i}=\phi_{j}]\Rightarrow[i=j]$ (atlas without repetion), (2) $M=\cup_{i\in I}U_{i}$ (the atlas covers $M$), (3) (intersection and restriction of charts) whenever $(U_{i}\cap U_{j})\not=\emptyset$, then there exists a unique $k\in I$ (which we denote by $k=[ij]$) such that $U_{k}=(U_{i}\cap U_{j}),\quad\forall y\in U_{k}:\phi_{k}(y)=\phi_{i}(y)\,.$ Sometimes, one may prefer to work with the following slightly weaker version of (3): (3â€™) for all $x\in(U_{i}\cap U_{j})$, there exists $k\in I$ such that $x\in U_{k}\subset(U_{i}\cap U_{j}),\quad\forall y\in U_{k}:\phi_{k}(y)=\phi_{i% }(y)\,.$ If $V$ and $M$ are equipped with topologies, we generally assume that the sets $U_{i}$ and $V_{i}$ are open, and that the $\phi_{i}$ are homeomorphisms. In this case, we will say that the atlas is saturated if every homeomorphism from a (non-empty) open subset of $M$ onto an open subset of $V$ is of the form $\phi_{k}$ with some $k\in I$.
Definition A.2. A subgroupoid $G=(G_{0},G_{1})$ of the full pseudogroup $({\mathcal{P}}(V),\mathcal{B}_{loc}(V))$ is called a pseudogroup of transformations of $V$ if: (PsG) assume that $U=\cup_{\alpha\in J}U_{\alpha}$ with all $U_{\alpha}\in G_{0}$ and that $f:U\to U^{\prime}\subset V$ is a bijection such that $\forall\alpha\in J$: $f|_{U_{\alpha}}\in G_{1}$. Then $f\in G_{1}$.
