Definition 2.6. Assume given a pseudogroup $G=(G_{0},G_{1})\subset({\mathcal{P}}(V),\mathcal{B}_{loc}(V))$ of transformations of the model space $V$ (cf. Def. A.2), we say that atlas data, and the atlas $\mathcal{A}$, are of type $G$ if $V_{k}\in G_{0}$ and $\phi_{ij}\in G_{1}$ whenever $k\in I$, $(i,j)\in E$. In case $(G_{0},G_{1})$ is the pseudogroup of locally defined diffeomorphisms of a topological $\mathbb{K}$-module $V$, we say that $\mathcal{A}$ is a smooth atlas.
Definition 6.1. Assume $(I,E,L,(\phi_{ij})_{(i,j)\in E})$ and $(I^{\prime},E^{\prime},L^{\prime},\phi_{i^{\prime}j^{\prime}})_{(i^{\prime},j^% {\prime})\in E^{\prime}}$ are atlas data belonging to manifolds with atlases $(M,\mathcal{A}),(M^{\prime},\mathcal{A}^{\prime})$. Morphism data between them are given by: a special natural relation $(F,R)$ between the e-pos $(I,E,L)$ and $(I^{\prime},E^{\prime},L^{\prime})$, that is, a pair of binary relations $(F,R)\subset({\mathcal{P}}(I\times I^{\prime})\times{\mathcal{P}}(E\times E^{% \prime}))$ such that: whenever $((i,k),(i^{\prime},k^{\prime}))\in R$, then $(i^{\prime},i)\in F$ and $(k^{\prime},k)\in F$, and, for each $(i^{\prime},i)\in F$, a map $f_{i^{\prime}i}:V_{i}\to V_{i^{\prime}}$ such that, whenever $\bigl{(}(i,k),(i^{\prime},k^{\prime})\bigr{)}\in R$, then $\xymatrix{V_{i}\ar[r]^{f_{i^{\prime}i}}\ar[d]^{\phi_{ik}}&V_{i}^{\prime}\ar[d]% ^{\phi_{k^{\prime}i^{\prime}}^{\prime}}\\ V_{k}\ar[r]^{f_{k^{\prime}k}}&V_{k}^{\prime}}$ Moreover, the following restriction and co-restriction properties shall be satisfied: (1) if $(i^{\prime},i)\in F$ and $k\leq i$, then $(i^{\prime},k)\in F$ and $f_{i^{\prime}k}=f_{i^{\prime}i}|_{V_{k}}$, (2) if $(i^{\prime},i)\in F$ and $i^{\prime}\leq m^{\prime}$, then $(m^{\prime},i)\in F$ and $\forall x\in V_{i}$: $f_{i^{\prime}i}(x)=f_{m^{\prime}i}(x)$. Morphism data are called full if $\forall k\in I$, $\forall x\in U_{k}$: $\exists i\leq k$, $\exists i^{\prime}\in I^{\prime}$: $x\in U_{i},(i^{\prime},i)\in F$.
Definition 2.1. Let ${\mathbf{2}}=\langle\{0,1\};\vee,\wedge,0,1\rangle$ be the $2$-element bounded lattice and let ${\mathbbm{2}}=\langle\{0,1\};\leqslant,{\mathscr{T}}\rangle$ be the discretely topologised $2$-element chain. For each bounded distributive lattice ${\mathbf{A}}=\langle A;\vee,\wedge,0,1\rangle$, define the Priestley space $H({\mathbf{A}})=\langle\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}({\mathbf{A}},{\mathbf{2}});% \leqslant,{\mathscr{T}}\rangle,$ with order and topology inherited from ${\mathbbm{2}}^{A}$. For each Priestley space ${\mathbb{X}}=\langle X;\leqslant,{\mathscr{T}}\rangle$, define the bounded distributive lattice $K({\mathbb{X}})=\langle\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}({\mathbb{X}},{\mathbbm{2}});% \vee,\wedge,0,1\rangle,$ with operations inherited from ${\mathbf{2}}^{X}$.
Definition 2.4. Let $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}$ be a variety of algebras that has a term reduct in $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}$ and let ${}^{\flat}\colon\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}\to\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}$ be the forgetful functor. Let $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$ be a category and let ${}^{\flat}\colon\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}\to\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}$ be a functor. Assume that $D\colon\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}\to\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$ and $E\colon\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}\to\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}$ are functors that yield a dual category equivalence between $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}$ and $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$ with unit $e\colon\operatorname{id}_{\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}}\to ED$ and counit $\varepsilon\colon\operatorname{id}_{\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}}\to DE$. We then say that $\langle D,E,e,\varepsilon\rangle$ is a restricted Priestley duality between $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}$ and $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$ (with underlying-Priestley-space functor ${}^{\flat}\colon\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}\to\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}$) if (1) the squares in Figure 1 commute, and (2) $e_{\mathbf{A}}^{\flat}=e_{{\mathbf{A}}^{\flat}}$ and $\varepsilon_{\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}=\varepsilon_{{\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}}$, for all ${\mathbf{A}}\in\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}$ and all ${\mathbb{X}}\in\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$. In particular, as a consequence of (1), we have (3) $D({\mathbf{A}})^{\flat}=H({\mathbf{A}}^{\flat})$, for all ${\mathbf{A}}\in\boldsymbol{\mathscr{A}}$, and (4) $E({\mathbb{X}})^{\flat}=K({\mathbb{X}}^{\flat})$, for all ${\mathbb{X}}\in\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$. It follows from (3) and (4) that $ED({\mathbf{A}})^{\flat}=KH({\mathbf{A}}^{\flat})$ and $DE({\mathbb{X}})^{\flat}=HK({\mathbb{X}}^{\flat})$. This guarantees that $e_{\mathbf{A}}^{\flat}$ and $e_{{\mathbf{A}}^{\flat}}$ have the same domain and codomain, as do $\varepsilon_{\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}$ and $\varepsilon_{{\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}}$, whence Condition (2) makes sense. It also follows at once from (3) and (4) that the underlying sets of $D({\mathbf{A}})$ and $E({\mathbb{X}})$ are $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}({\mathbf{A}}^{\flat},{\mathbf{2}})$ and $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}({\mathbb{X}}^{\flat},{\mathbbm{2}})$, respectively. A morphism $\varphi\colon{\mathbb{X}}\to{\mathbb{Y}}$ in $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{X}}$ will be called $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}$-surjective if its underlying Priestley morphism $\varphi^{\flat}\colon{\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}\to{\mathbb{Y}}^{\flat}$ is surjective. Similarly, $\varphi$ is a $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}$-embedding if its underlying Priestley morphism is an embedding of Priestley spaces.
Definition 5.1. Let $c\colon\{0,1\}\to\{0,1\}$ be the usual Boolean complementation: $c(0)=1$ and $c(1)=0$. For each Cornish algebra ${\mathbf{A}}=\langle A;\vee,\wedge,F^{\mathbf{A}},0,1\rangle$, define the Cornish space $D({\mathbf{A}})=\langle\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}({\mathbf{A}}^{\flat},{\mathbf{% 2}});F^{D({\mathbf{A}})},\leqslant,{\mathscr{T}}\rangle,$ where $\langle\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}({\mathbf{A}}^{\flat},{\mathbf{2}});\leqslant,{% \mathscr{T}}\rangle$ is the Priestley space dual to the underlying bounded distributive lattice ${\mathbf{A}}^{\flat}$ and, for all $f\in F$, the unary operation $f^{D({\mathbf{A}})}$ is given by $f^{D({\mathbf{A}})}(x)=\begin{cases}x\circ f^{\mathbf{A}},&\text{ if $f\in F^{% +}$,}\\ c\circ x\circ f^{\mathbf{A}},&\text{ if $f\in F^{-}$,}\end{cases}$ for all $x\colon{\mathbf{A}}^{\flat}\to{\mathbf{2}}$. For each Cornish space ${\mathbb{X}}=\langle X;F^{\mathbb{X}},\leqslant,{\mathscr{T}}\rangle$, define the Cornish algebra $E({\mathbb{X}})=\langle\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}({\mathbb{X}}^{\flat},{\mathbbm% {2}});\vee,\wedge,F^{E({\mathbb{X}})},0,1\rangle,$ where $\langle\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}({\mathbb{X}}^{\flat},{\mathbbm{2}});\vee,% \wedge,0,1\rangle$ is the bounded distributive lattice dual to the Priestley space ${\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}$, and, for all $f\in F$, the unary operation $f^{E({\mathbb{X}})}$ is given by $f^{E({\mathbb{X}})}(\alpha)=\begin{cases}\alpha\circ f^{\mathbb{X}},&\text{ if% $f\in F^{+}$,}\\ c\circ\alpha\circ f^{\mathbb{X}},&\text{ if $f\in F^{-}$,}\end{cases}$ for all $\alpha\colon{\mathbb{X}}^{\flat}\to{\mathbbm{2}}$.
Definition 2.2. â€¢ For each homomorphism $\varphi\colon{\mathbf{A}}\to{\mathbf{B}}$ in $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}$, define $H(\varphi)\colon H({\mathbf{B}})\to H({\mathbf{A}})$ by $H(\varphi)(x):=x\circ\varphi$, for all $x\colon{\mathbf{B}}\to{\mathbf{2}}$. â€¢ For each morphism $\psi\colon{\mathbb{X}}\to{\mathbb{Y}}$ in $\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}$, define $K(\psi)\colon K({\mathbb{Y}})\to K({\mathbb{X}})$ by $K(\psi)(\alpha)=\alpha\circ\psi$, for all $\alpha\colon{\mathbb{Y}}\to{\mathbbm{2}}$. â€¢ For each ${\mathbf{A}}\in\boldsymbol{\mathscr{D}}$, the homomorphism $e_{\mathbf{A}}\colon{\mathbf{A}}\to KH({\mathbf{A}})$ is given by evaluation, that is, $e_{\mathbf{A}}(a)(x)=x(a)$, for all $a\in A$ and $x\colon{\mathbf{A}}\to{\mathbf{2}}$. â€¢ For each ${\mathbb{X}}\in\boldsymbol{\mathscr{P}}$, the morphism $\varepsilon_{\mathbb{X}}\colon{\mathbb{X}}\to HK({\mathbb{X}})$ is given by evaluation, that is, $\varepsilon_{\mathbb{X}}(x)(\alpha)=\alpha(x)$, for all $x\in X$ and $\alpha\colon{\mathbb{X}}\to{\mathbbm{2}}$.
Definition \thedefinition. An algebraic triangulated category ${\mathbf{T}}$ has a strongly unique (respectively, semi-strongly unique) enhancement if moreover $\mathsf{F}$ can be chosen so that there is an isomorphism of exact functors $\mathsf{E}\cong\mathsf{E}^{\prime}\circ\mathrm{H}^{0}(\mathsf{F})$ (respectively, there is an isomorphism $\mathsf{E}(C)\cong\mathsf{E}^{\prime}(\mathrm{H}^{0}(\mathsf{F})(C))$ in ${\mathbf{T}}$, for every $C\in{\mathbf{C}}$).
Definition \thedefinition. A localizing subcategory ${\mathbf{L}}$ of ${\mathbf{T}}$ is a smashing subcategory if the inclusion functor $\iota\colon{\mathbf{L}}\hookrightarrow{\mathbf{T}}$ has a right adjoint $\iota^{R}$ which commutes with small coproducts.
Definition \thedefinition. A dg category is a category ${\mathbf{C}}$ such that, for all $A,B,C$ in ${\mathbf{C}}$, the morphism spaces ${\mathbf{C}}\left(A,B\right)$ are $\mathbb{Z}$-graded $\Bbbk$-modules with a differential $d\colon{\mathbf{C}}\left(A,B\right)\to{\mathbf{C}}\left(A,B\right)$ of degree $1$ and the composition maps ${\mathbf{C}}(B,C)\otimes_{\Bbbk}{\mathbf{C}}(A,B)\to{\mathbf{C}}(A,C)$, $g\otimes f\mapsto g\circ f$, are morphisms of complexes.
Definition \thedefinition. A dg functor $\mathsf{F}\colon{\mathbf{C}}_{1}\to{\mathbf{C}}_{2}$ between two dg categories is a functor such that the map $\mathsf{F}_{A,B}$ is a morphisms of complexes of $\Bbbk$-modules, for every $A,B\in{\mathbf{C}}_{1}$.
Definition \thedefinition. An exact functor $\mathsf{F}\colon\mathrm{D}^{b}(X_{1})\to\mathrm{D}^{b}(X_{2})$ is a Fourierâ€“Mukai functor (or of Fourierâ€“Mukai type) if there exists $E\in\mathrm{D}^{b}(X_{1}\times X_{2})$ and an isomorphism of exact functors $\mathsf{F}\cong\Phi_{E}$. The object $E$ is called Fourierâ€“Mukai kernel.
Definition \thedefinition. A triangulated category is algebraic if it has an enhancement.
Definition \thedefinition. A morphism $f\in{\mathbf{Hqe}}({\mathbf{C}}_{1},{\mathbf{C}}_{2})$ is a dg lift (or simply a lift) of $\mathsf{F}$ if there is an isomorphism of exact functors $\mathsf{F}\cong\mathsf{E}_{2}\circ\mathrm{H}^{0}(f)\circ\mathsf{E}_{1}^{-1}$.
Definition \thedefinition. An algebraic triangulated category ${\mathbf{T}}$ has a unique enhancement if, given two enhancements $({\mathbf{C}},\mathsf{E})$ and $({\mathbf{C}}^{\prime},\mathsf{E}^{\prime})$ of ${\mathbf{T}}$, there exists a quasi-functor $\mathsf{F}\colon{\mathbf{C}}\to{\mathbf{C}}^{\prime}$ such that $\mathrm{H}^{0}(\mathsf{F})$ is an equivalence.
Definition \thedefinition. A dg functor $\mathsf{F}\colon{\mathbf{C}}_{1}\to{\mathbf{C}}_{2}$ is a quasi-equivalence, if the maps $\mathsf{F}_{A,B}$ are quasi-isomorphisms, for every $A,B\in{\mathbf{C}}_{1}$, and $\mathrm{H}^{0}(\mathsf{F})$ is an equivalence.
Definition \thedefinition. A dg enhancement (or simply an enhancement) of a triangulated category ${\mathbf{T}}$ is a pair $({\mathbf{C}},\mathsf{E})$, where ${\mathbf{C}}$ is a pretriangulated dg category and $\mathsf{E}\colon\mathrm{H}^{0}({\mathbf{C}})\to{\mathbf{T}}$ is an exact equivalence.
Definition \thedefinition. A dg category ${\mathbf{C}}$ is pretriangulated if the essential image of the functor $\mathrm{H}^{0}(\mathsf{Y}^{{\mathbf{C}}}_{\mathrm{dg}})\colon\mathrm{H}^{0}({% \mathbf{C}})\to\mathrm{H}^{0}(\mathrm{dgMod}({\mathbf{C}}))$ is a triangulated subcategory.
Definition \thedefinition. The category ${\mathbf{T}}$ is well generated if there exists a small set ${\mathbf{S}}$ of objects in ${\mathbf{T}}$ satisfying the following properties: (G1) An object $X\in{\mathbf{T}}$ is isomorphic to $0$, if and only if ${\mathbf{T}}(S,X[j])=0$, for all $S\in{\mathbf{S}}$ and all $j\in\mathbb{Z}$; (G2) For every small set of maps $\{X_{i}\to Y_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ in ${\mathbf{T}}$, the induced map ${\mathbf{T}}(S,\coprod_{i}X_{i})\to{\mathbf{T}}(S,\coprod_{i}Y_{i})$ is surjective for all $S\in{\mathbf{S}}$, if ${\mathbf{T}}(S,X_{i})\to{\mathbf{T}}(S,Y_{i})$ is surjective, for all $i\in I$ and all $S\in{\mathbf{S}}$; (G3) There exists a regular cardinal $\alpha$ such that every object of ${\mathbf{S}}$ is $\alpha$-small.
Definition 1.6. A functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathbf{C}\rightarrow\mathbf{D}$ is called left (right) exact if it commutes with finite limits (colimits). $\mathcal{F}$ is called exact if it is both left and right exact.
