Definition 5.16. Assume that a category $\mathbf{K}$ admits cofiltered limits. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a precosheaf with values in $\mathbf{K}$, and let $x\in X$. The costalk of $\mathcal{A}$ at $x$ is $\mathcal{A}^{x}{:=}\underleftarrow{\lim}_{U\in J\left(x\right)}\mathcal{A}% \left(U\right)$ where $J\left(x\right)$ is the family of open neighborhoods of $x$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathbf{K}$ be a category. Assume that $\mathbf{K}$ is complete in (2) below, and cocomplete in (3) below. Given $G,H\in\mathbf{K,~{}}Z\in\mathbf{Set,}$ let us consider (1) $Hom_{\mathbf{K}}\left(G,H\right)\in\mathbf{Set;}$ (2) $Hom_{\mathbf{Set}}\left(Z,G\right){:=}\mathop{\displaystyle\prod}\limits_{Z}G% \in\mathbf{K;}$ (3) $G\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}Z=Z\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}G{:=}\mathop{\displaystyle% \coprod}\limits_{Z}G\in\mathbf{K;}$
Definition 4.15. Let $X=\left(\mathbf{C}_{X},Cov\left(X\right)\right)$ be a small site, and let $\mathbf{K}$ be a complete category. (1) A presheaf $\mathcal{A}$ on $X$ with values in $\mathbf{K}$ is a functor $\mathcal{A}:\left(\mathbf{C}_{X}\right)^{op}\rightarrow\mathbf{K.}$ (2) A presheaf $\mathcal{A}$ is separated provided that for any $U\in\mathbf{C}_{X}$ $\mathcal{A}\left(U\right)=Hom_{\mathbf{Set}^{\left(\mathbf{C}_{X}\right)^{op}}% }\left(h_{U},\mathcal{A}\right)\longrightarrow Hom_{\mathbf{Set}^{\left(% \mathbf{C}_{X}\right)^{op}}}\left(R,\mathcal{A}\right)$ is a monomorphism for any covering sieve $R$ over $U$. (3) A presheaf $\mathcal{A}$ is a sheaf provided that for any $U\in\mathbf{C}_{X}$ $\mathcal{A}\left(U\right)=Hom_{\mathbf{Set}^{\left(\mathbf{C}_{X}\right)^{op}}% }\left(h_{U},\mathcal{A}\right)\longrightarrow Hom_{\mathbf{Set}^{\left(% \mathbf{C}_{X}\right)^{op}}}\left(R,\mathcal{A}\right)$ is an isomorphism for any covering sieve $R$ over $U$.
Definition 1.14. Let $\lambda$ be a regular cardinal, and $\mathbf{C}$ be a category. (1) A poset is called $\lambda$-directed provided that every subset of cardinality smaller than $\lambda$ has an upper bound. A diagram $\mathcal{D}:\mathbf{I\rightarrow C}$ where $\mathbf{I}$ is a $\lambda$-directed poset is called a $\lambda$-directed diagram. A poset or a diagram is called directed if it is $\aleph_{0}$-directed. (2) An object $U$ of $\mathbf{C}$ is called $\lambda$-presentable provided that $h^{U}=Hom_{\mathbf{C}}\left(U,\_\right):\mathbf{C}\longrightarrow\mathbf{Set}$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits. $U$ is called finitely presentable if it is $\aleph_{0}$-presentable. (3) $\mathbf{C}$ is called locally $\lambda$-presentable provided that it is cocomplete, and has a set $A$ of $\lambda$-presentable objects such that every object is a $\lambda$-directed colimit of objects from $A$. $\mathbf{C}$ is called locally presentable if it is locally $\lambda$-presentable for some regular cardinal $\lambda$. $\mathbf{C}$ is called locally finitely presentable if it is locally $\aleph_{0}$-presentable.
Definition 5.5. Let $X$ be a small site, and $\mathbf{K}$ be a category (cocomplete and closed under cofiltered limits). For a precosheaf $\mathcal{A}$, define a precosheaf $\left(\mathcal{A}\right)_{+}^{\mathbf{K}}$ (or simply $\mathcal{A}_{+})$ by the following: $\mathcal{A}_{+}\left(U\right)=\underset{R}{\underleftarrow{\lim}}~{}\underset{% \left(V\rightarrow U\right)\in\mathbf{C}_{R}}{\underrightarrow{\lim}}\mathcal{% A}\left(V\right)=\underset{R}{\underleftarrow{\lim}}~{}\left(\mathcal{A}% \otimes_{\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{C}_{X}}}R\right).$ where $R\subseteq h^{U}$ runs over all covering sieves over $U$.
Definition 1.26. For a (pointed) topological space $X$, define its pro-homotopy pro-sets $pro\text{-}\pi_{n}\left(X\right){:=}\left(\pi_{n}\left(Y_{j}\right)\right)_{j% \in\mathbf{J}}$ where $X\rightarrow\left(Y_{j}\right)_{j\in\mathbf{J}}$ is an $H\left(\mathbf{Pol}\right)$-expansion if $n=0$, and an $H\left(\mathbf{Pol}_{\ast}\right)$-expansion if $n\geq 1$.
Definition 1.4. A category $\mathbf{C}$ is called complete if it admits small limits, and cocomplete if it admits small colimits.
Definition 1.8. Given $U\in\mathbf{C}$, let $h_{U}:\mathbf{C}^{op}\longrightarrow\mathbf{Set},~{}h^{U}:\mathbf{C}% \longrightarrow\mathbf{Set},$ be the following functors: $h_{U}\left(V\right){:=}Hom_{\mathbf{C}}\left(V,U\right),~{}h^{U}\left(V\right)% {:=}Hom_{\mathbf{C}}\left(U,V\right).$
Definition 4.3. A Grothendieck site (or simply a site) $X$ is a pair $\left(\mathbf{C}_{X},Cov\left(X\right)\right)$ where $\mathbf{C}_{X}$ is a category, and $Cov\left(X\right)=\mathop{\displaystyle\bigcup}\limits_{U\in\mathbf{C}_{X}}Cov% \left(U\right),$ where $Cov\left(U\right)$ are the sets of covering sieves over $U$, satisfying the axioms GT1-GT4 from [KS06, Definition 16.1.2], or, equivalently, the axioms T1-T3 from [SGA72, Definition II.1.1]. The site is called small iff $\mathbf{C}_{X}$ is a small category.
Definition 5.19. Let $\mathbf{K}$ admit cofiltered limits, and let $f:\mathcal{A\rightarrow B}$ be a morphism in the category of precosheaves $\mathbf{pCS}\left(X,\mathbf{K}\right)$. We say that $f$ is a local isomorphism iff $f^{x}:\mathcal{A}^{x}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}^{x}$ is an isomorphism for any $x\in X$. In a situation when $\mathbf{K}\subseteq\mathbf{L}$, and $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}\in\mathbf{pCS}\left(X,\mathbf{K}\right)\subseteq% \mathbf{pCS}\left(X,\mathbf{L}\right),$ we will say that $f$ is $\mathbf{K}$-local (respectively $\mathbf{L}$-local) isomorphism iff $\left(f\right)_{\mathbf{K}}^{x}:\left(\mathcal{A}\right)_{\mathbf{K}}^{x}% \rightarrow\left(\mathcal{B}\right)_{\mathbf{K}}^{x}$ (respectively $\left(f\right)_{\mathbf{L}}^{x}:\left(\mathcal{A}\right)_{\mathbf{L}}^{x}% \rightarrow\left(\mathcal{B}\right)_{\mathbf{L}}^{x}$) is an isomorphism for any $x\in X$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{X}=\left(X_{i}\right)_{i\in\mathbf{I}}\in\mathbf{Pro}\left(\mathbf{% Set}\right)$, and $Y\in\mathbf{K}$. Define $\mathcal{X}\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}Y=Y\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}\mathcal{X}\in% \mathbf{Pro}\left(\mathbf{K}\right)$ by $\mathcal{X}\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}Y=\left(X_{i}\otimes_{\mathbf{Set}}Y\right)_{% i\in\mathbf{I}}.$
